"# Chapter 12 — Grade 12: Pre-Calculus

## Opening: The Gateway to the Infinite

Pre-calculus sits at a remarkable threshold in the history of mathematics. By the late 17th century, mathematicians had accumulated centuries of geometric knowledge, algebraic techniques, and astronomical observation—but they lacked a systematic way to handle change, motion, and the infinitely small. Pre-calculus is the collection of tools and ideas that made calculus *possible*: understanding functions as objects in their own right, wrestling with what happens \"as we approach\" a value, representing motion and force as vectors, organizing data into matrices, thinking in polar coordinates where circles are natural, and recognizing patterns in infinite series.

**History & development.** The ideas in this chapter come from many sources. Vectors emerged from physics and engineering in the 19th century (Hamilton, Grassmann, Gibbs) as a way to talk about forces and velocities without clumsy component notation. Matrices appeared slightly earlier in the study of linear equations (Cayley, Sylvester) and became indispensable in quantum mechanics and computer graphics. Polar coordinates trace back to Newton and Jakob Bernoulli, who realized that spirals and planetary orbits are *simpler* when you measure angle and radius instead of x and y. The intuitive notion of a limit—what a function \"approaches\" even if it never quite gets there—was debated for centuries before Cauchy and Weierstrass made it rigorous in the 1800s. Infinite series, from Zeno's paradoxes through Euler's audacious manipulations, asked whether you can sum infinitely many numbers and get a finite answer.

**Uses & utility in the world.** These tools are everywhere. Vectors model velocity, force, electric fields, and pixel colors. Matrices power computer graphics (every 3D game), cryptography, search-engine ranking (PageRank), and data science (linear regression, neural networks). Polar coordinates simplify antenna radiation patterns, planetary motion, and any problem with circular symmetry. Limits underpin all of calculus, which means all of physics, engineering, and economics. Series let you approximate transcendental functions (sin, cos, e^x, ln) to arbitrary precision—every calculator and computer uses them.

**What we'll cover and why.** We'll explore function families (polynomials, rationals, exponentials, logs, trig) and build fluency transforming and combining them. We'll develop an intuitive feel for limits by making tables and graphs that \"zoom in\" on a value. We'll learn to add, scale, and measure vectors, and to multiply matrices—operations that seem abstract until you see them rotate a point or solve three equations in three unknowns. We'll plot polar curves (roses, spirals, cardioids) where the *angle* is the input and the *radius* is the output. And we'll investigate infinite series: when they converge, when they diverge, and how to sum them.

**Its utility in Motoi.** On the dot-matrix canvas, pre-calculus is the bridge from static pictures to *motion and transformation*. Vectors let the runtime represent direction and speed—an arrow, a velocity, a force pushing a particle. Matrices let her rotate, scale, and shear entire shapes in one operation. Polar coordinates make it natural to draw spirals, petals, and anything that spins. Limits give her a way to *zoom*: to ask what a function does near a point, even if the point itself is undefined. Series let her approximate curves and compute transcendental functions from scratch, pixel by pixel. Every tool in this chapter expands what she can *do*—and every tool here is a stepping-stone to calculus, where change itself becomes the subject.

We call it math, but we're really moving dots—and in this chapter, those dots start to *transform, approach, and spiral* in new ways.

---

## Topic 1: Function Families — Recognizing the Cast

Before calculus, you need to know the *characters*: the families of functions that show up again and again. Polynomials, rationals, exponentials, logarithms, and trigonometric functions each have a shape, a personality, and a role to play. Pre-calculus is partly about fluency—recognizing a function's family at a glance, predicting its behavior, and knowing how to transform it (shift, stretch, reflect).

**History & development.** The concept of a *function* as an abstract mapping from inputs to outputs took centuries to crystallize. Early mathematicians (Babylonians, Greeks) worked with specific relationships—areas, volumes, astronomical tables—but didn't have a general notation. Descartes and Fermat introduced coordinates and algebraic curves in the 1600s. Leibniz coined the word \"function\" around 1694, and Euler made it central to analysis in the 1700s. The exponential function e^x and the natural logarithm ln(x) emerged from the study of compound interest and areas under hyperbolas. Trigonometric functions, originally geometric ratios in right triangles, were reinterpreted as functions of a real variable (radian measure) and became essential in physics and engineering.

**Uses & utility in the world.** Polynomials model everything from projectile motion (parabolas) to economic cost curves. Rational functions (ratios of polynomials) appear in physics (inverse-square laws, RC circuits), chemistry (reaction rates), and statistics (Cauchy distributions). Exponentials model growth and decay—population, radioactive decay, compound interest, viral spread. Logarithms compress large ranges (earthquake magnitudes, sound decibels, star brightness) and solve for time in exponential processes. Trig functions model oscillation—sound waves, light waves, alternating current, planetary orbits, the rising and setting of the sun.

**What we'll cover and why.** We'll write and plot examples from each family, observe their shapes, and practice transformations. This fluency is the foundation for calculus: derivatives and integrals are defined *per family*, and you'll learn rules for each one.

**Its utility in Motoi.** On the dot-matrix canvas, function families are *shapes you can draw*. A polynomial is a curve, a rational function has asymptotes you can see, an exponential rises or falls, a log curve crawls upward forever, a sine wave oscillates. Recognizing the family means knowing what you'll see before you plot it—and knowing how to *make* the shape you want by choosing the right function.

---

### Example 1.1: Polynomial — A Cubic Curve

<!-- BUILD: Plot y = x^3 - 3x over [-3, 3], mark the local max and min. Render as Cartesian plot with gridlines. -->

```scheme
(define (f x)
  (* x (- (* x x) 3)))

(plot/function f -3.0 3.0
  '((title . \"Cubic: y = x³ - 3x\")
    (y-min . -4.0)
    (y-max . 4.0)
    (grid . #t)))
```

[VISUAL: Cartesian plot from x = -3 to 3. The cubic curve dips to a local minimum near x = 1, rises through the origin, and climbs to a local maximum near x = -1. Gridlines visible.]

A polynomial is a sum of powers of x. This one has degree 3 (cubic), so it can wiggle twice—creating one local max and one local min. Polynomials are smooth, continuous, and defined everywhere.

---

### Example 1.2: Rational Function — Hyperbola with Asymptotes

<!-- BUILD: Plot y = 1/x over [-4, 4], skip x=0 (division by zero). Show vertical asymptote at x=0 and horizontal asymptote y=0. Render as Cartesian plot. -->

```scheme
(define (g x)
  (if (= x 0.0)
      'nan
      (/ 1.0 x)))

(plot/function g -4.0 4.0
  '((title . \"Rational: y = 1/x\")
    (y-min . -4.0)
    (y-max . 4.0)
    (grid . #t)))
```

[VISUAL: Cartesian plot from x = -4 to 4. Two branches of a hyperbola: one in the upper-right quadrant approaching the y-axis from the right and the x-axis from above, one in the lower-left quadrant mirroring it. Vertical gap at x=0 (undefined). The axes themselves are asymptotes.]

A rational function is a ratio of polynomials. This one, 1/x, has a vertical asymptote at x=0 (where the denominator is zero) and a horizontal asymptote at y=0 (as x grows, 1/x shrinks toward zero). Rational functions often have \"forbidden\" values and asymptotes—places the curve can't touch.

---

### Example 1.3: Exponential Growth — e^x

<!-- BUILD: Plot y = e^x over [-2, 2]. Show the rapid rise. Render as Cartesian plot. -->

```scheme
(define (h x)
  (calc/exp x))

(plot/function h -2.0 2.0
  '((title . \"Exponential: y = eˣ\")
    (y-min . 0.0)
    (y-max . 8.0)
    (grid . #t)))
```

[VISUAL: Cartesian plot from x = -2 to 2. The curve hugs the x-axis for negative x (approaching zero but never touching), passes through (0, 1), and rises steeply for positive x, reaching nearly 8 at x=2. Classic exponential growth shape.]

The exponential function e^x grows faster than any polynomial. It's always positive, passes through (0, 1), and its slope at any point equals its value at that point (a fact you'll prove in calculus). Exponentials model unrestricted growth.

---

### Example 1.4: Logarithm — The Inverse of Exponential

<!-- BUILD: Plot y = ln(x) over [0.1, 5]. Show the slow climb and vertical asymptote at x=0. Render as Cartesian plot. -->

```scheme
(define (j x)
  (if (<= x 0.0)
      'nan
      (calc/log x)))

(plot/function j 0.1 5.0
  '((title . \"Logarithm: y = ln(x)\")
    (y-min . -3.0)
    (y-max . 2.0)
    (grid . #t)))
```

[VISUAL: Cartesian plot from x = 0.1 to 5. The curve plunges down toward negative infinity near x=0 (vertical asymptote), crosses the x-axis at x=1 (ln(1)=0), and climbs slowly, reaching about 1.6 at x=5. Logarithmic growth is slow but unbounded.]

The natural logarithm ln(x) is the inverse of e^x. It's only defined for positive x, grows without bound (but slowly), and passes through (1, 0). Logarithms \"undo\" exponentials: ln(e^x) = x and e^(ln(x)) = x.

---

### Example 1.5: Trigonometric — Sine Wave

<!-- BUILD: Plot y = sin(x) over [0, 2π]. Show one complete oscillation. Render as Cartesian plot. -->

```scheme
(define pi 3.141592653589793)

(define (k x)
  (calc/sin x))

(plot/function k 0.0 (* 2.0 pi)
  '((title . \"Trigonometric: y = sin(x)\")
    (y-min . -1.5)
    (y-max . 1.5)
    (grid . #t)))
```

[VISUAL: Cartesian plot from x = 0 to 2π (about 6.28). The sine wave starts at (0, 0), rises to a peak of 1 at π/2, crosses zero at π, dips to -1 at 3π/2, and returns to zero at 2π. One smooth, periodic oscillation.]

The sine function oscillates between -1 and 1 with period 2π. It's the prototypical wave. Cosine is a shifted sine: cos(x) = sin(x + π/2). These functions are the heartbeat of anything that vibrates or rotates.

---

### Example 1.6: Transformations — Shifting and Stretching a Parabola

<!-- BUILD: Plot y = 2(x-1)^2 + 3 over [-1, 4]. Show how the parabola vertex moved from (0,0) to (1,3) and the \"a\" coefficient stretches it vertically. Render as Cartesian plot. -->

```scheme
(define (parabola x)
  (+ (* 2.0 (* (- x 1.0) (- x 1.0))) 3.0))

(plot/function parabola -1.0 4.0
  '((title . \"Transformed Parabola: y = 2(x-1)² + 3\")
    (y-min . 0.0)
    (y-max . 20.0)
    (grid . #t)))
```

[VISUAL: Cartesian plot from x = -1 to 4. A parabola opening upward with vertex at (1, 3). The curve is narrower (steeper) than the standard y=x^2 because of the coefficient 2. Vertex shifted right 1 and up 3 from the origin.]

Transformations move and reshape functions without changing their family. The general form y = a(x - h)^2 + k shifts the vertex of a parabola to (h, k) and stretches it by a factor of |a|. If a is negative, the parabola flips upside down. Every function family has a \"parent\" shape and transformations that shift, stretch, reflect, or compress it.

---

### Example 1.7: Composition — Nesting Functions

<!-- BUILD: Plot y = e^(sin(x)) over [0, 2π]. Show how the exponential \"rides\" the sine wave, creating oscillating peaks. Render as Cartesian plot. -->

```scheme
(define (composite x)
  (calc/exp (calc/sin x)))

(plot/function composite 0.0 (* 2.0 pi)
  '((title . \"Composition: y = e^(sin(x))\")
    (y-min . 0.0)
    (y-max . 3.0)
    (grid . #t)))
```

[VISUAL: Cartesian plot from x = 0 to 2π. The curve oscillates between about 0.37 (e^(-1)) and about 2.72 (e^1), following the shape of the sine wave but always positive and \"exponentially weighted.\" Peaks where sin(x) peaks, troughs where sin(x) is most negative.]

Composition—feeding one function into another—creates new behaviors. Here, the sine wave becomes the *input* to the exponential, so the output oscillates between e^(-1) and e^1. Composition is one of the most powerful tools in mathematics: you can build arbitrarily complex functions from simple families.

---

### Example 1.8: Piecewise Function — Different Rules on Different Intervals

<!-- BUILD: Plot a piecewise function: y = x^2 for x < 0, y = sqrt(x) for x >= 0. Show the sharp corner at the origin. Render as Cartesian plot. -->

```scheme
(define (piecewise x)
  (if (< x 0.0)
      (* x x)
      (calc/sqrt x)))

(plot/function piecewise -3.0 9.0
  '((title . \"Piecewise: y = x² (x<0), y = √x (x≥0)\")
    (y-min . 0.0)
    (y-max . 9.0)
    (grid . #t)))
```

[VISUAL: Cartesian plot from x = -3 to 9. For x < 0, a parabola opening upward (y = x^2) descends to the origin. For x ≥ 0, a square-root curve climbs slowly from the origin. The two pieces meet at (0, 0) but the slope changes abruptly—a \"corner.\"]

A piecewise function uses different formulas on different parts of its domain. They appear in tax brackets, shipping rates, and physics (different forces in different regions). Piecewise functions can be continuous (no jumps) or discontinuous (sudden leaps), and they can have corners where the pieces meet.

---

## Topic 2: Limits — What Does the Function Approach?

A limit asks: as x gets closer and closer to some value c, what does f(x) get closer and closer to? The answer might be a number, infinity, or \"it doesn't approach anything.\" Limits are the foundation of calculus—the derivative and the integral are both defined as limits.

**History & development.** The ancient Greeks (Zeno's paradoxes, Archimedes' method of exhaustion) grappled with the infinite and the infinitesimal but lacked precise language. Newton and Leibniz invented calculus in the late 1600s using intuitive notions of \"fluxions\" and \"infinitely small\" quantities—powerful but logically shaky. Mathematicians argued for over a century about what these meant. In the 1820s, Augustin-Louis Cauchy introduced the epsilon-delta definition: \"for every ε > 0, there exists δ > 0 such that…\" Karl Weierstrass refined it further in the 1850s, giving calculus the rigorous foundation it has today. Limits formalize the idea of \"getting arbitrarily close.\"

**Uses & utility in the world.** Limits underpin all of calculus, which means all of physics and engineering. They let you define instantaneous velocity (a limit of average velocities over shrinking intervals), the slope of a curve at a point (a limit of secant lines), the area under a curve (a limit of Riemann sums), and the sum of an infinite series (a limit of partial sums). Every time you compute a derivative, an integral, or a Taylor series, you're invoking a limit.

**What we'll cover and why.** We'll compute limits numerically by making tables of values that \"approach\" a point from the left and right. We'll see limits that exist and equal the function value (continuous functions), limits that exist but differ from the function value (removable discontinuities), limits that blow up to infinity (vertical asymptotes), and limits that oscillate or don't exist at all. This intuitive approach prepares you for the formal definition in calculus.

**Its utility in Motoi.** On the dot-matrix canvas, a limit is a *zoom*: you pick a point, shrink the window around it, and watch what the function does as you get closer. You can visualize a limit as a sequence of dots marching toward a target value—or shooting off to infinity. Limits let the runtime ask questions like \"what happens *near* x=0?\" even when x=0 itself is forbidden. It's the mathematics of \"almost\" and \"approaching,\" and it's essential for understanding change.

---

### Example 2.1: A Simple Limit — Approaching a Finite Value

<!-- BUILD: Compute lim(x→2) of x^2 by evaluating at 1.9, 1.99, 1.999, 2.001, 2.01, 2.1. Show the values approaching 4. Render as a table (text output). -->

```scheme
(define (f x) (* x x))

(define xs '(1.9 1.99 1.999 2.001 2.01 2.1))

(define (limit-table func vals)
  (map (lambda (x)
         (list x (func x)))
       vals))

(limit-table f xs)
;; Output:
;; ((1.9 3.61) (1.99 3.9601) (1.999 3.996001) (2.001 4.004001) (2.01 4.0401) (2.1 4.41))
```

[VISUAL: Text table with two columns: x and f(x). As x approaches 2 from below (1.9, 1.99, 1.999) and from above (2.001, 2.01, 2.1), f(x) approaches 4. The limit is 4, and f(2) = 4 as well—this is a continuous function at x=2.]

When a function is continuous at a point, the limit as x approaches that point equals the function value. Here, lim(x→2) x^2 = 4, and f(2) = 4. The function is \"well-behaved.\"

---

### Example 2.2: A Removable Discontinuity — The Limit Exists but the Function Is Undefined

<!-- BUILD: Compute lim(x→0) of (sin(x)/x) by evaluating at ±0.1, ±0.01, ±0.001. Show the values approaching 1. Render as a table (text output). -->

```scheme
(define (g x)
  (if (= x 0.0)
      'nan
      (/ (calc/sin x) x)))

(define xs2 '(-0.1 -0.01 -0.001 0.001 0.01 0.1))

(limit-table g xs2)
;; Output (approximate):
;; ((-0.1 0.998334...) (-0.01 0.999983...) (-0.001 0.999999...)
;;  (0.001 0.999999...) (0.01 0.999983...) (0.1 0.998334...))
```

[VISUAL: Text table. As x approaches 0 from both sides, (sin(x)/x) approaches 1, even though the function is undefined at x=0 (division by zero). This is the famous \"sinc\" limit, foundational in calculus. The discontinuity is \"removable\"—if you *defined* g(0) = 1, the function would be continuous.]

A limit can exist even when the function is undefined at that point. This happens when a \"hole\" in the graph can be \"filled in\" by defining the function value to equal the limit. lim(x→0) (sin(x)/x) = 1 is one of the most important limits in calculus—it's used to prove the derivative of sin(x).

---

### Example 2.3: Infinite Limit — Approaching a Vertical Asymptote

<!-- BUILD: Compute lim(x→0⁺) of 1/x by evaluating at 0.1, 0.01, 0.001. Show the values growing without bound. Render as a table (text output). -->

```scheme
(define (h x) (/ 1.0 x))

(define xs3 '(0.1 0.01 0.001 0.0001))

(limit-table h xs3)
;; Output:
;; ((0.1 10.0) (0.01 100.0) (0.001 1000.0) (0.0001 10000.0))
```

[VISUAL: Text table. As x approaches 0 from the right (positive side), 1/x grows larger and larger—10, 100, 1000, 10000. The limit is +∞ (the function \"blows up\"). From the left, it would approach -∞. There is a vertical asymptote at x=0.]

When a function grows without bound as x approaches a point, we say the limit is infinite. This signals a vertical asymptote. The limit \"doesn't exist\" in the sense that it's not a finite number, but the behavior is still well-defined: the function shoots off to infinity.

---

### Example 2.4: Limit at Infinity — Horizontal Asymptote

<!-- BUILD: Compute lim(x→∞) of 1/x by evaluating at 10, 100, 1000, 10000. Show the values approaching 0. Render as a table (text output). -->

```scheme
(define xs4 '(10.0 100.0 1000.0 10000.0))

(limit-table h xs4)
;; Output:
;; ((10.0 0.1) (100.0 0.01) (1000.0 0.001) (10000.0 0.0001))
```

[VISUAL: Text table. As x grows (10, 100, 1000, 10000), 1/x shrinks toward 0 (0.1, 0.01, 0.001, 0.0001). lim(x→∞) 1/x = 0. There is a horizontal asymptote at y=0.]

A limit at infinity asks what happens as x grows without bound. If the function approaches a finite value, that value is a horizontal asymptote. Here, 1/x approaches 0 as x → ∞, so y=0 is a horizontal asymptote.

---

### Example 2.5: One-Sided Limits — Left and Right Differ

<!-- BUILD: Compute lim(x→0⁻) and lim(x→0⁺) of |x|/x (the sign function). Show left limit = -1, right limit = +1. Render as a table (text output). -->

```scheme
(define (sign-func x)
  (cond
    ((> x 0.0) 1.0)
    ((< x 0.0) -1.0)
    (else 'nan)))

(define xs-left '(-0.1 -0.01 -0.001))
(define xs-right '(0.001 0.01 0.1))

(list 'left (limit-table sign-func xs-left)
      'right (limit-table sign-func xs-right))
;; Output:
;; (left ((-0.1 -1.0) (-0.01 -1.0) (-0.001 -1.0))
;;  right ((0.001 1.0) (0.01 1.0) (0.1 1.0)))
```

[VISUAL: Two text tables. Left table: approaching 0 from negative x gives -1 consistently. Right table: approaching 0 from positive x gives +1 consistently. The two one-sided limits differ, so the two-sided limit does not exist. There is a jump discontinuity at x=0.]

If the left-hand limit and right-hand limit at a point are different, the (two-sided) limit does not exist. The function \"jumps\" from one value to another. This is a jump discontinuity.

---

### Example 2.6: Oscillating Limit — No Limit Exists

<!-- BUILD: Compute lim(x→0) of sin(1/x) by evaluating at 0.1, 0.01, 0.001. Show the values oscillating wildly. Render as a table (text output). -->

```scheme
(define (oscillator x)
  (if (= x 0.0)
      'nan
      (calc/sin (/ 1.0 x))))

(define xs5 '(0.1 0.05 0.01 0.005 0.001))

(limit-table oscillator xs5)
;; Output (approximate):
;; ((0.1 -0.544021...) (0.05 -0.912945...) (0.01 0.506366...)
;;  (0.005 -0.958924...) (0.001 0.826880...))
```

[VISUAL: Text table. The values of sin(1/x) as x→0 do not settle down—they jump between positive and negative values, oscillating faster and faster. The limit does not exist because the function does not approach any single value. This is wild oscillation.]

Some functions oscillate infinitely many times near a point and never settle on a value. For these, the limit does not exist. sin(1/x) near x=0 is the classic example: as x shrinks, 1/x grows, and sin completes more and more cycles.

---

### Example 2.7: Using the Limit Verb — Numeric Limit from calc/

<!-- BUILD: Use calc/limit to compute lim(x→0) of (e^x - 1)/x numerically. Show it approaches 1. Render as a text output. -->

```scheme
(define (exponential-limit x)
  (/ (- (calc/exp x) 1.0) x))

(calc/limit exponential-limit 0.0 0.001)
;; Output (approximate): 1.000000...
```

[VISUAL: Text output showing the numeric limit value close to 1. The calc/limit verb automates the \"approach\" process, evaluating the function at points progressively closer to the target and returning the limiting value.]

The `calc/limit` verb performs numerical limit estimation by evaluating the function at points approaching the target from both sides. This is the automated version of making a limit table by hand. lim(x→0) (e^x - 1)/x = 1 is another fundamental limit in calculus (used to prove the derivative of e^x).

---

### Example 2.8: Graphical Limit — Zooming In on a Point

<!-- BUILD: Plot (x^2 - 4)/(x - 2) near x=2 over [1.5, 2.5]. Show the \"hole\" at x=2 and the line approaching y=4. Render as Cartesian plot. -->

```scheme
(define (removable x)
  (if (= x 2.0)
      'nan
      (/ (- (* x x) 4.0) (- x 2.0))))

(plot/function removable 1.5 2.5
  '((title . \"Limit: (x²-4)/(x-2) near x=2\")
    (y-min . 2.0)
    (y-max . 6.0)
    (grid . #t)))
```

[VISUAL: Cartesian plot from x=1.5 to 2.5. A straight line with slope 2, passing through points near y=4 when x is near 2. There is a visible gap (hole) at exactly x=2 where the function is undefined. The line approaches y=4 as x approaches 2 from either side.]

Graphically, a removable discontinuity looks like a \"hole\" in an otherwise continuous curve. The function (x^2 - 4)/(x - 2) simplifies to (x+2)(x-2)/(x-2) = x+2 for x ≠ 2, which is a line. At x=2, the original function is undefined (0/0), but the limit is 2+2 = 4. If we \"fill the hole\" by defining f(2) = 4, the function becomes continuous.

---

## Topic 3: Vectors — Arrows in Space

A vector is a quantity with both magnitude (length) and direction. Unlike a scalar (just a number), a vector can point somewhere—north, up, or at a 37° angle. Vectors are written as ordered lists of components: in two dimensions, (a, b); in three dimensions, (a, b, c). You can add vectors (tip-to-tail), scale them (stretch or shrink), measure their length, and compute angles between them.

**History & development.** Vectors emerged in the 19th century from the study of forces, velocities, and electromagnetic fields. William Rowan Hamilton invented quaternions (an extension of complex numbers) in 1843, which included a vector-like component. Josiah Willard Gibbs and Oliver Heaviside, working independently in the 1880s, developed the modern vector notation and algebra (dot product, cross product) that's taught today. Hermann Grassmann had earlier (1844) created a more abstract \"extension theory\" that included vector spaces, but it was largely ignored until later. Vectors became central to physics (relativity, quantum mechanics) and engineering (statics, dynamics, electromagnetism) in the 20th century.

**Uses & utility in the world.** Vectors represent displacement (from here to there), velocity (speed and direction), acceleration (change in velocity), force (push or pull), electric and magnetic fields, momentum, and more. In computer graphics, vectors represent points in space, directions of light rays, and surface normals. In machine learning, a data point is a vector, and high-dimensional vectors encode everything from word meanings (word embeddings) to images (pixel arrays).

**What we'll cover and why.** We'll create vectors, add and subtract them, scale them, compute their magnitude (length), normalize them (shrink to unit length), and compute the dot product (a measure of \"alignment\" that gives the angle between vectors). In three dimensions, we'll compute the cross product (a vector perpendicular to two given vectors). These operations are the grammar of vector algebra.

**Its utility in Motoi.** On the dot-matrix canvas, a vector is an *arrow*: a displacement from one point to another, or a direction and magnitude. The runtime can add velocity vectors to simulate motion, compute the normal to a surface to determine lighting, or find the direction from a point to a target. Vectors let her think geometrically about movement and orientation—\"which way, and how far?\"

---

### Example 3.1: Creating and Displaying a Vector

<!-- BUILD: Create a 2D vector (3, 4) and print it. Render as text output. -->

```scheme
(define v (vec/make 3.0 4.0))
(vec/->string v)
;; Output: \"(3.000, 4.000)\"
```

[VISUAL: Text output showing the vector as an ordered pair.]

A vector in two dimensions has two components: an x-component and a y-component. `(vec/make 3.0 4.0)` creates the vector ⟨3, 4⟩. You can think of it as an arrow from the origin to the point (3, 4), or as a displacement \"3 units right, 4 units up.\"

---

### Example 3.2: Vector Addition — Tip-to-Tail

<!-- BUILD: Add vectors (3, 4) and (1, 2). Print the result (4, 6). Render as text output. -->

```scheme
(define v1 (vec/make 3.0 4.0))
(define v2 (vec/make 1.0 2.0))
(define v-sum (vec/+ v1 v2))
(vec/->string v-sum)
;; Output: \"(4.000, 6.000)\"
```

[VISUAL: Text output showing (4, 6). Geometrically, you'd place the tail of v2 at the tip of v1; the sum is the arrow from the tail of v1 to the tip of v2.]

Vector addition is component-wise: (a, b) + (c, d) = (a+c, b+d). Geometrically, you line up the vectors tip-to-tail; the sum is the vector from the start of the first to the end of the second.

---

### Example 3.3: Vector Subtraction — Difference

<!-- BUILD: Subtract (1, 2) from (3, 4). Print the result (2, 2). Render as text output. -->

```scheme
(define v-diff (vec/- v1 v2))
(vec/->string v-diff)
;; Output: \"(2.000, 2.000)\"
```

[VISUAL: Text output showing (2, 2). Geometrically, v1 - v2 points from the tip of v2 to the tip of v1 when both are drawn from the origin.]

Vector subtraction is also component-wise: (a, b) - (c, d) = (a-c, b-d). The difference v1 - v2 gives the vector from v2 to v1.

---

### Example 3.4: Scaling a Vector — Multiply by a Scalar

<!-- BUILD: Scale the vector (3, 4) by 2. Print the result (6, 8). Render as text output. -->

```scheme
(define v-scaled (vec/scale v1 2.0))
(vec/->string v-scaled)
;; Output: \"(6.000, 8.000)\"
```

[VISUAL: Text output showing (6, 8). Geometrically, the vector is twice as long but points in the same direction.]

Scaling (or scalar multiplication) multiplies each component by a number. Scaling by 2 doubles the length; scaling by -1 reverses the direction; scaling by 0.5 halves the length.

---

### Example 3.5: Magnitude — Length of a Vector

<!-- BUILD: Compute the magnitude of (3, 4). Print the result 5. Render as text output. -->

```scheme
(define len (vec/norm v1))
len
;; Output: 5.0
```

[VISUAL: Text output showing 5.0. The magnitude of (3, 4) is √(3² + 4²) = √25 = 5, the length of the hypotenuse of a 3-4-5 right triangle.]

The magnitude (or norm, or length) of a vector ⟨a, b⟩ is √(a² + b²) in two dimensions, √(a² + b² + c²) in three dimensions. It's the distance from the origin to the point (a, b, c), or the \"size\" of the displacement.

---

### Example 3.6: Normalizing a Vector — Unit Vector

<!-- BUILD: Normalize (3, 4) to get a unit vector in the same direction. Print the result (0.6, 0.8). Render as text output. -->

```scheme
(define v-unit (vec/normalize v1))
(vec/->string v-unit)
;; Output: \"(0.600, 0.800)\"
```

[VISUAL: Text output showing (0.6, 0.8). This is (3, 4) divided by its length 5: (3/5, 4/5). The result has magnitude 1 and points in the same direction as the original.]

Normalizing a vector means scaling it so its magnitude is 1. The unit vector in the direction of v is v / ||v||. Unit vectors are useful for representing pure direction without regard to magnitude.

---

### Example 3.7: Dot Product — Measuring Alignment

<!-- BUILD: Compute the dot product of (3, 4) and (1, 2). Print the result 11. Render as text output. -->

```scheme
(define dot-prod (vec/dot v1 v2))
dot-prod
;; Output: 11.0
```

[VISUAL: Text output showing 11.0. The dot product is 3×1 + 4×2 = 3 + 8 = 11.]

The dot product of ⟨a, b⟩ and ⟨c, d⟩ is ac + bd. It equals ||v1|| ||v2|| cos(θ), where θ is the angle between the vectors. If the dot product is zero, the vectors are perpendicular. If positive, the angle is acute; if negative, obtuse.

---

### Example 3.8: Angle Between Vectors

<!-- BUILD: Compute the angle between (3, 4) and (1, 2). Print the angle in degrees. Render as text output. -->

```scheme
(define angle-rad (vec/angle-between v1 v2))
(define angle-deg (geom/->degrees angle-rad))
angle-deg
;; Output (approximate): 10.305°
```

[VISUAL: Text output showing approximately 10.3 degrees. The vectors point in nearly the same direction (both are in the first quadrant with similar slopes), so the angle is small.]

The angle θ between two vectors satisfies cos(θ) = (v1 · v2) / (||v1|| ||v2||). The `vec/angle-between` verb computes this angle in radians; `geom/->degrees` converts it to degrees.

---

### Example 3.9: Cross Product in 3D — Perpendicular Vector

<!-- BUILD: Compute the cross product of (1, 0, 0) and (0, 1, 0). Print the result (0, 0, 1). Render as text output. -->

```scheme
(define i (vec/make 1.0 0.0 0.0))
(define j (vec/make 0.0 1.0 0.0))
(define k (vec/cross i j))
(vec/->string k)
;; Output: \"(0.000, 0.000, 1.000)\"
```

[VISUAL: Text output showing (0, 0, 1). The cross product of the unit vector in the x-direction and the unit vector in the y-direction is the unit vector in the z-direction—perpendicular to both.]

The cross product of two 3D vectors is a third vector perpendicular to both, with magnitude ||v1|| ||v2|| sin(θ). The direction follows the right-hand rule. The cross product is only defined in three dimensions (and seven, with octonions, but that's exotic). It's used to find normal vectors to surfaces, compute torque, and determine the orientation of coordinate systems.

---

### Example 3.10: Vector Projection — Component Along a Direction

<!-- BUILD: Project (3, 4) onto (1, 0). Print the result (3, 0). Render as text output. -->

```scheme
(define v-dir (vec/make 1.0 0.0))
(define proj-scalar (/ (vec/dot v1 v-dir) (vec/dot v-dir v-dir)))
(define v-proj (vec/scale v-dir proj-scalar))
(vec/->string v-proj)
;; Output: \"(3.000, 0.000)\"
```

[VISUAL: Text output showing (3, 0). Projecting (3, 4) onto the x-axis gives the x-component, (3, 0). This is the \"shadow\" of v1 in the direction of v-dir.]

The projection of v onto u is ((v · u) / (u · u)) u. It's the component of v in the direction of u—the part of v that \"lines up\" with u. Projections are used in physics (finding the component of a force in a given direction) and computer graphics (shadow calculations, lighting).

---

## Topic 4: Matrices — Arrays of Numbers

A matrix is a rectangular array of numbers, written in rows and columns. Matrices can represent systems of linear equations, transformations of space (rotations, scalings, shears), and data tables. You can add and subtract matrices (component-wise), multiply a matrix by a scalar, and multiply two matrices (a more intricate operation that combines rows and columns).

**History & development.** The study of matrices grew out of the need to solve systems of linear equations. Ancient Chinese mathematicians (around 200 BCE) used arrays of numbers and Gaussian-elimination-like methods, recorded in *The Nine Chapters on the Mathematical Art*. In the West, determinants appeared in the 17th century (Leibniz, Seki Takakazu), but the modern concept of a matrix emerged in the 19th century. Arthur Cayley introduced matrix notation and algebra in 1858. James Joseph Sylvester coined the term \"matrix\" (from the Latin for \"womb,\" a place where things are formed). Matrices became central to quantum mechanics (operators as matrices), relativity (tensors as generalizations of matrices), and, in the 20th century, computer graphics, cryptography, and data science.

**Uses & utility in the world.** Matrices represent transformations: rotation, scaling, reflection, shear, projection. Every 3D graphics pipeline uses 4×4 matrices to transform vertices from object space through world space, view space, and finally to screen space. Matrices solve systems of linear equations (Ax = b) via Gaussian elimination or matrix inversion. They appear in network analysis (adjacency matrices), Markov chains (transition matrices), and machine learning (weight matrices in neural networks, covariance matrices in statistics). Eigenvalues and eigenvectors of matrices reveal fundamental modes of a system—principal components in data, resonance frequencies in structures, steady states in Markov processes.

**What we'll cover and why.** We'll create matrices, add and multiply them, compute the transpose, find the determinant (a scalar that tells you whether the matrix is invertible), and solve small linear systems. These are the core operations of linear algebra, and they prepare you for multivariable calculus, optimization, and data science.

**Its utility in Motoi.** On the dot-matrix canvas, a matrix is a *transformation*. Multiply a point (represented as a column vector) by a 2×2 matrix and you rotate, scale, or shear it. Multiply a set of points by a matrix and you transform an entire shape. Matrices let the runtime think in terms of operations that reshape space—spin this triangle, scale that square, project this 3D shape onto the 2D screen. Every animated rotation or zoom is a matrix multiplication under the hood.

---

### Example 4.1: Creating a Matrix

<!-- BUILD: Create a 2×2 matrix [[1, 2], [3, 4]]. Print it. Render as text output. -->

```scheme
(define A (matrix/make '((1.0 2.0) (3.0 4.0))))
(matrix/->string A)
;; Output:
;; \"[[1.000, 2.000],
;;   [3.000, 4.000]]\"
```

[VISUAL: Text output showing a 2×2 matrix with two rows and two columns. The first row is [1, 2], the second row is [3, 4].]

A matrix is specified as a list of rows, where each row is a list of numbers. This 2×2 matrix has 2 rows and 2 columns. Matrices can be any size: 3×3, 4×4, 2×5, etc.

---

### Example 4.2: Matrix Addition

<!-- BUILD: Add [[1, 2], [3, 4]] and [[5, 6], [7, 8]]. Print the result [[6, 8], [10, 12]]. Render as text output. -->

```scheme
(define B (matrix/make '((5.0 6.0) (7.0 8.0))))
(define A-plus-B (matrix/+ A B))
(matrix/->string A-plus-B)
;; Output:
;; \"[[6.000, 8.000],
;;   [10.000, 12.000]]\"
```

[VISUAL: Text output showing the sum matrix. Each entry is the sum of the corresponding entries in A and B.]

Matrix addition is component-wise: you add corresponding entries. Both matrices must have the same dimensions.

---

### Example 4.3: Scalar Multiplication — Scaling a Matrix

<!-- BUILD: Multiply [[1, 2], [3, 4]] by 3. Print the result [[3, 6], [9, 12]]. Render as text output. -->

```scheme
(define A-scaled (matrix/scale A 3.0))
(matrix/->string A-scaled)
;; Output:
;; \"[[3.000, 6.000],
;;   [9.000, 12.000]]\"
```

[VISUAL: Text output showing each entry of A multiplied by 3.]

Scalar multiplication scales every entry in the matrix by the same number.

---

### Example 4.4: Matrix Multiplication — Combining Transformations

<!-- BUILD: Multiply [[1, 2], [3, 4]] by [[5, 6], [7, 8]]. Print the result [[19, 22], [43, 50]]. Render as text output. -->

```scheme
(define A-times-B (matrix/* A B))
(matrix/->string A-times-B)
;; Output:
;; \"[[19.000, 22.000],
;;   [43.000, 50.000]]\"
```

[VISUAL: Text output showing the product matrix. The (i, j) entry is the dot product of the i-th row of A with the j-th column of B. For example, entry (1,1) is 1×5 + 2×7 = 5 + 14 = 19.]

Matrix multiplication is *not* component-wise. To multiply A (m×n) by B (n×p), the number of columns in A must equal the number of rows in B. The result is an m×p matrix. The entry in row i, column j of the product is the dot product of row i of A with column j of B. Matrix multiplication is associative and distributive but *not* commutative: in general, AB ≠ BA.

---

### Example 4.5: Identity Matrix — The \"Do Nothing\" Transformation

<!-- BUILD: Create the 2×2 identity matrix [[1, 0], [0, 1]]. Multiply it by A and show the result is A. Render as text output. -->

```scheme
(define I (matrix/identity 2))
(define A-times-I (matrix/* A I))
(matrix/->string A-times-I)
;; Output:
;; \"[[1.000, 2.000],
;;   [3.000, 4.000]]\"
```

[VISUAL: Text output showing A unchanged. The identity matrix has 1s on the diagonal and 0s elsewhere. Multiplying by I leaves a matrix (or vector) unchanged: AI = A and IA = A.]

The identity matrix is the multiplicative identity for matrices—it plays the role of the number 1. For any matrix A, A × I = I × A = A.

---

### Example 4.6: Transpose — Flipping Rows and Columns

<!-- BUILD: Transpose [[1, 2], [3, 4]]. Print the result [[1, 3], [2, 4]]. Render as text output. -->

```scheme
(define A-transpose (matrix/transpose A))
(matrix/->string A-transpose)
;; Output:
;; \"[[1.000, 3.000],
;;   [2.000, 4.000]]\"
```

[VISUAL: Text output showing the matrix with rows and columns swapped. The first row of A (1, 2) becomes the first column of A^T; the second row (3, 4) becomes the second column.]

The transpose of a matrix is obtained by swapping rows and columns: the entry in row i, column j of A becomes the entry in row j, column i of A^T. Transposing twice returns the original matrix: (A^T)^T = A.

---

### Example 4.7: Determinant — A Scalar Property

<!-- BUILD: Compute the determinant of [[1, 2], [3, 4]]. Print the result -2. Render as text output. -->

```scheme
(define det-A (matrix/determinant A))
det-A
;; Output: -2.0
```

[VISUAL: Text output showing -2.0. For a 2×2 matrix [[a, b], [c, d]], the determinant is ad - bc. Here, 1×4 - 2×3 = 4 - 6 = -2.]

The determinant is a scalar value computed from a square matrix. It tells you whether the matrix is invertible (det ≠ 0) or singular (det = 0). Geometrically, the absolute value of the determinant is the factor by which the matrix scales area (in 2D) or volume (in 3D). A negative determinant means the transformation reverses orientation (flips space).

---

### Example 4.8: Solving a 2×2 Linear System — Ax = b

<!-- BUILD: Solve [[1, 2], [3, 4]] × [x, y] = [5, 6]. Print the solution [-4, 4.5]. Render as text output. -->

```scheme
(define b-vec (vec/make 5.0 6.0))
(define x-solution (linalg/solve A b-vec))
(vec/->string x-solution)
;; Output: \"(-4.000, 4.500)\"
```

[VISUAL: Text output showing the solution vector. Multiply A by this vector and you get [5, 6]: 1×(-4) + 2×4.5 = -4 + 9 = 5; 3×(-4) + 4×4.5 = -12 + 18 = 6. ✓]

A system of linear equations can be written in matrix form Ax = b, where A is the coefficient matrix, x is the vector of unknowns, and b is the vector of constants. If det(A) ≠ 0, the system has a unique solution x = A^(-1) b. The `linalg/solve` verb computes this solution (typically via Gaussian elimination or LU decomposition, not by explicitly computing the inverse, which is numerically unstable).

---

### Example 4.9: Rotating a Point with a Matrix

<!-- BUILD: Create a 2×2 rotation matrix for 90° counterclockwise. Multiply it by the point (1, 0). Print the result (0, 1). Render as text output. -->

```scheme
(define theta (/ (* 2.0 3.141592653589793) 4.0))  ; π/2 radians = 90°
(define cos-t (calc/cos theta))
(define sin-t (calc/sin theta))
(define R (matrix/make (list (list cos-t (- sin-t))
                              (list sin-t cos-t))))
(define point (vec/make 1.0 0.0))
(define rotated (matrix/* R point))
(vec/->string rotated)
;; Output (approximate): \"(0.000, 1.000)\"
```

[VISUAL: Text output showing (0, 1). The point (1, 0) on the positive x-axis is rotated 90° counterclockwise to (0, 1) on the positive y-axis. The rotation matrix is [[cos(θ), -sin(θ)], [sin(θ), cos(θ)]].]

A rotation matrix in 2D is [[cos(θ), -sin(θ)], [sin(θ), cos(θ)]], where θ is the angle of rotation (counterclockwise, in radians). Multiplying a point (as a column vector) by this matrix rotates it around the origin. This is how 2D graphics engines rotate sprites and shapes.

---

### Example 4.10: Eigenvalues of a 2×2 Matrix

<!-- BUILD: Compute the eigenvalues of [[4, 1], [2, 3]]. Print the result [5, 2]. Render as text output. -->

```scheme
(define M (matrix/make '((4.0 1.0) (2.0 3.0))))
(define eigenvals (linalg/eigenvalues-2x2 M))
eigenvals
;; Output: (5.0 2.0)
```

[VISUAL: Text output showing the two eigenvalues. An eigenvalue λ is a scalar such that Mv = λv for some nonzero vector v (the eigenvector). For this matrix, the characteristic polynomial is λ² - 7λ + 10 = 0, which factors as (λ - 5)(λ - 2) = 0, giving eigenvalues 5 and 2.]

Eigenvalues are scalars that reveal fundamental properties of a matrix. They tell you the factors by which the matrix stretches space along certain directions (the eigenvectors). Eigenvalues are central to stability analysis, vibration modes, principal component analysis, Google's PageRank, and quantum mechanics. Computing eigenvalues for larger matrices is a major topic in numerical linear algebra.

---

## Topic 5: Polar Coordinates — Radius and Angle

So far, we've described points in the plane using Cartesian coordinates (x, y): horizontal and vertical distances from the origin. Polar coordinates use a different system: (r, θ), where r is the distance from the origin and θ is the angle from the positive x-axis. Polar coordinates are natural for problems with circular or spiral symmetry—planets orbiting a star, ripples in a pond, flower petals, radar screens.

**History & development.** The idea of using distance and angle to locate a point is ancient—navigators and astronomers have always thought in terms of direction and distance. But the formal system of polar coordinates emerged in the 17th century. Isaac Newton used a coordinate system resembling polar coordinates in his work on planetary motion. Jakob Bernoulli studied the logarithmic spiral in polar form in the 1690s and requested it be engraved on his tombstone (though a different spiral ended up there due to a stonemason's error). Grégoire de Saint-Vincent and Bonaventura Cavalieri also explored polar-like ideas. By the 18th century, polar coordinates were well-established, and Euler used them extensively.

**Uses & utility in the world.** Polar coordinates simplify many problems. Planetary orbits (Kepler's laws) are ellipses with the sun at one focus—much easier to describe in polar form (r = a(1 - e²)/(1 + e cos θ)) than Cartesian. Antenna radiation patterns, speakers' sound dispersion, and sonar/radar displays are naturally polar. Many engineering problems (rotating machinery, circular waveguides, electromagnetism around wires) have circular symmetry and become simpler in polar coordinates. In mathematics, certain integrals (area, arc length) are easier to compute in polar form.

**What we'll cover and why.** We'll convert between Cartesian and polar coordinates, plot polar curves (circles, spirals, roses, cardioids), and understand how radius varies with angle. These curves are often strikingly beautiful and symmetric, and they reveal a different \"grammar\" for describing space.

**Its utility in Motoi.** On the dot-matrix canvas, polar coordinates let the runtime draw spirals, petals, and radial patterns with simple formulas. Instead of thinking \"where is x and y,\" she thinks \"how far from the center, and at what angle?\" This is the natural way to draw a clock face, a flower, a radar sweep, or a spinning pattern. Polar plotting is one of the most visually rewarding modes—small changes in a polar function produce dramatic, symmetric designs.

---

### Example 5.1: Converting Cartesian to Polar

<!-- BUILD: Convert the Cartesian point (3, 4) to polar. Print (r, θ) = (5, 0.927 radians ≈ 53.13°). Render as text output. -->

```scheme
(define x 3.0)
(define y 4.0)
(define r (calc/sqrt (+ (* x x) (* y y))))
(define theta (calc/atan2 y x))
(define theta-deg (geom/->degrees theta))
(list 'r r 'theta-rad theta 'theta-deg theta-deg)
;; Output: (r 5.0 theta-rad 0.927295... theta-deg 53.130...)
```

[VISUAL: Text output showing r = 5, θ ≈ 0.927 radians ≈ 53.13°. The point (3, 4) in Cartesian is 5 units from the origin at an angle of about 53° from the positive x-axis.]

To convert (x, y) to (r, θ): r = √(x² + y²), θ = atan2(y, x). The function atan2(y, x) returns the angle in the correct quadrant (unlike atan(y/x), which loses sign information).

---

### Example 5.2: Converting Polar to Cartesian

<!-- BUILD: Convert the polar point (r=5, θ=π/3) to Cartesian. Print (x, y) ≈ (2.5, 4.330). Render as text output. -->

```scheme
(define r2 5.0)
(define theta2 (/ 3.141592653589793 3.0))  ; π/3 radians = 60°
(define x2 (* r2 (calc/cos theta2)))
(define y2 (* r2 (calc/sin theta2)))
(list 'x x2 'y y2)
;; Output: (x 2.5 y 4.330127...)
```

[VISUAL: Text output showing x ≈ 2.5, y ≈ 4.33. The point 5 units from the origin at 60° corresponds to (2.5, 4.33) in Cartesian coordinates.]

To convert (r, θ) to (x, y): x = r cos(θ), y = r sin(θ). This is the standard parametrization of a circle.

---

### Example 5.3: Plotting a Circle in Polar — r = constant

<!-- BUILD: Plot the polar curve r = 3 (a circle of radius 3) over θ ∈ [0, 2π]. Render as a polar plot. -->

```scheme
(define (circle-polar theta) 3.0)

(plot/parametric
  (lambda (t) (* (circle-polar t) (calc/cos t)))
  (lambda (t) (* (circle-polar t) (calc/sin t)))
  0.0 (* 2.0 3.141592653589793)
  '((title . \"Polar Circle: r = 3\")
    (grid . #t)))
```

[VISUAL: Polar plot (rendered as Cartesian with parametric x(t), y(t)). A perfect circle of radius 3 centered at the origin. In polar, a constant r gives a circle; in Cartesian, this would be x² + y² = 9, harder to write.]

In polar coordinates, r = constant is a circle centered at the origin. The beauty of polar: the simplest equation (r = 3) describes a circle directly. In Cartesian, you need x² + y² = r².

---

### Example 5.4: Archimedean Spiral — r = θ

<!-- BUILD: Plot the polar curve r = θ over θ ∈ [0, 4π]. Show the spiral expanding outward. Render as a polar plot. -->

```scheme
(define (spiral theta) theta)

(plot/parametric
  (lambda (t) (* (spiral t) (calc/cos t)))
  (lambda (t) (* (spiral t) (calc/sin t)))
  0.0 (* 4.0 3.141592653589793)
  '((title . \"Archimedean Spiral: r = θ\")
    (grid . #t)))
```

[VISUAL: Polar plot showing a spiral that starts at the origin and winds outward, making two full loops (θ goes from 0 to 4π). The radius increases linearly with the angle—equal spacing between successive turns.]

The Archimedean spiral, r = θ, increases radius uniformly with angle. It appears in nature (nautilus shells, galaxies) and in mechanics (grooves on a vinyl record, clock springs). It's the simplest spiral.

---

### Example 5.5: Rose Curve — r = cos(2θ)

<!-- BUILD: Plot the polar curve r = cos(2θ) over θ ∈ [0, 2π]. Show the four-petal rose. Render as a polar plot. -->

```scheme
(define (rose theta)
  (calc/cos (* 2.0 theta)))

(plot/parametric
  (lambda (t) (* (rose t) (calc/cos t)))
  (lambda (t) (* (rose t) (calc/sin t)))
  0.0 (* 2.0 3.141592653589793)
  '((title . \"Rose Curve: r = cos(2θ)\")
    (aspect . equal)
    (grid . #t)))
```

[VISUAL: Polar plot showing a symmetric four-petal rose. Each petal is a loop where r goes from 0 to a maximum and back to 0. The curve is traced as θ sweeps from 0 to 2π. The petals are evenly spaced 90° apart.]

A rose curve r = cos(nθ) or r = sin(nθ) has n petals if n is odd, and 2n petals if n is even. Here, n = 2, so we get 4 petals. These curves are strikingly symmetric and beautiful—\"mathematical flowers.\"

---

### Example 5.6: Cardioid — r = 1 + cos(θ)

<!-- BUILD: Plot the polar curve r = 1 + cos(θ) over θ ∈ [0, 2π]. Show the heart-shaped curve. Render as a polar plot. -->

```scheme
(define (cardioid theta)
  (+ 1.0 (calc/cos theta)))

(plot/parametric
  (lambda (t) (* (cardioid t) (calc/cos t)))
  (lambda (t) (* (cardioid t) (calc/sin t)))
  0.0 (* 2.0 3.141592653589793)
  '((title . \"Cardioid: r = 1 + cos(θ)\")
    (aspect . equal)
    (grid . #t)))
```

[VISUAL: Polar plot showing a heart-shaped curve with a cusp at the origin (where r = 0 when θ = π). The curve is symmetric about the x-axis. \"Cardioid\" means \"heart-shaped.\"]

The cardioid appears in acoustics (the pickup pattern of certain microphones), optics (caustics formed by reflecting light off a circular mirror), and mathematics (the boundary of the main bulb of the Mandelbrot
")
